{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Sandra }} [[Category:1951 births]] [[Category:Living people]] [[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]] [[Category:American philosophers]] [[Category:Philosophers of science]] [[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]] [[Category:American historians of philosophy]] [[Category:Philosophy of biology]] [[Category:Philosophers of social science]] [[Category:American women historians]]

The '''Logicians''' or '''School of Names''' ({{zh |c = 名家 |p = Míngjiā}})  was a school of [[Chinese philosophy]] that grew out of [[Mohism]] during the [[Warring States period]] in 479–221 BCE. It is also sometimes called the '''School of Forms and Names''' ({{zh |c = 形名家 |p = Xíngmíngjiā |w = Hsing<sup>2</sup>-ming<sup>2</sup>-chia<sup>1</sup>}}).<ref name="Needham 1956">{{harvnb|Needham|1956|page=185}}</ref> [[Deng Xi]] has been named its founder.

==Overview==
The philosophy of the Logicians is often considered to be akin to those of the [[sophists]] or of the [[dialectician]]s. [[Joseph Needham]] notes that their works have been lost, except for the partially preserved  ''[[Gongsun Longzi]]'', and the paradoxes of Chapter 33 of the ''[[Zhuangzi (book)|Zhuangzi]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Needham|1956|page=697}}</ref> Needham considers the disappearance of the greater part of  ''[[Gongsun Longzi]]'' one of the worst losses in the ancient Chinese books, as what remains is said to reach the highest point of ancient Chinese philosophical writing.<ref name="Needham 1956" />
[[File:Birth Places of Chinese Philosophers.png|300px|thumb|Birth places of notable Chinese philosophers from Hundred Schools of Thought in Zhou Dynasty. Philosophers of Logicianism are marked by circles in blue.]]

One of the few surviving lines from the school, "a one-foot stick, every day take away half of it, in a myriad ages it will not be exhausted," resembles [[Zeno's paradoxes]]. However, some of their other aphorisms seem contradictory or unclear when taken out of context, for example, "Dogs are not hounds."<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/school-names/paradoxes.html Miscellaneous Paradoxes]</ref>

They were opposed by the Later [[Mohists]] for their paradoxes.<ref>{{harvnb|Van Norden|2011|page=111}}</ref>

