{{Infobox person | name = Viktor Sonnenfeld | image = | imagesize = | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1902|01|21}} | birth_place = [[Petrijevci]], [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Empire]], (now [[Croatia]]) | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1969|03|30|1902|01|21}} | death_place = [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] | relations = | spouse = | children = | alma_mater = [[University of Zagreb]] | occupation = [[Translation|Translator]], [[Philosophy|philosopher]] | nationality = [[Croats|Croat]] }}
'''Viktor D. Sonnenfeld''' (21 January 1902 – 30 March 1969) was prominent [[Croatian people|Croatian]] translator and philosopher.
==Biography== Sonnenfeld was born to a [[Jew]]ish family in [[Petrijevci]], near [[Osijek]], on 21 January 1902. In Osijek, Sonnenfeld finished elementary school and gymnasium, and in [[Zagreb]] and [[Marseille]], he studied philosophy. All his life Sonnenfeld worked and acted in Osijek. He worked at the Osijek daily "Hrvatski list", and for 20 years at "[[Glas Slavonije]]" as the editor of cultural section. Sonnenfeld translated works of German philosophers and writers such as; [[Immanuel Kant]], [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and others. Overall, from German to Croatian, he translated 940 titles. [[City and University Library in Osijek]] has stored Sonnenfeld personal library, a legacy of the 3345 book.<ref name="gdksb">{{hr icon}} Gradska i sveučilišna knjižnica Osijek (Glasnik Društva knjižničara Slavonije i Baranje); Legat Viktora D. Sonnenfeld u Gradskoj i sveučilišnoj knjižnici Osijek; stranica 153, 154, 155; Broj 1-2 (2007-2008).</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osijek.hr/index.php/cro/Osijek/Osjecki-spomendan/OSJECKI-SPOMENDAN-21.-sijecnja|title=Osječki spomendan 21. siječnja|quote=U Petrijevcima, mjestu nedaleko od Osijeka, u židovskoj obitelji rođen Viktor Sonnenfeld. (In Petrijevci, village near Osijek, Viktor Sonnenfeld was born into a Jewish family.)|publisher=[[Osijek]]|date=2010-01-21|language=Croatian|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osijek.hr/index.php/cro/Osijek/Osjecki-spomendan/OSJECKI-SPOMENDAN-30.-ozujka|title=Osječki spomendan 30. ožujka|publisher=[[Osijek]]|date=2010-03-30|language=Croatian|accessdate=17 November 2012}}</ref> Sonnenfeld retired and died in 1969, and was buried at Jewish part of the cemetery Sv. Ana, Osijek.<ref name="gdksb"/><ref>{{hr icon}} Ukop d.o.o. Osijek: Viktor Sonnenfeld, Groblje Sv. Ana XII-4-5</ref>
==Translations== From [[German language|German]] to [[Croatian language|Croatian]]: *''Filozofija povijesti'' ([[Lectures on the Philosophy of History]], 1951) *''Dvije rasprave'' ([[Prolegomena to Any Future Metaphysics]], 1953) *''Fenomenologija duha'' ([[The Phenomenology of Spirit]], 1955) *''Odabrane filozofske rasprave'' (Die Bestimmung des Menschen, 1956)
